description: Rules and guidelines for the CMS3 Admin project
globs: 
  - pages/**/*.php
  - partials/components/**/*.php
  - scripts/**/*.js
  - styles/**/*.css
alwaysApply: true
rules:
  - name: Directory Structure
    description: >
      Ensure all files are placed in their respective directories:
      - Page-specific PHP files in `pages/`
      - Reusable components in `partials/components/`
      - JavaScript files in `scripts/`
      - CSS files in `styles/`

  - name: File Naming Conventions
    description: >
      Use lowercase letters and hyphens for file names.
      Ensure names are descriptive of the file's purpose.

  - name: PHP Includes
    description: >
      Use consistent paths for including partials.
      Utilize a configuration file for common settings and paths.

  - name: CSS and JavaScript
    description: >
      Use CSS variables for theming and colors.
      Implement event delegation in JavaScript for performance.

  - name: Accessibility
    description: >
      Use ARIA roles and labels for accessibility.
      Ensure all interactive elements are keyboard navigable.

  - name: Version Control
    description: >
      Commit changes frequently with descriptive messages.
      Use branches for new features or major changes.

  - name: Code Style
    description: >
      Follow consistent coding styles across the project:
      - Use 2 spaces for indentation in HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.
      - Use 4 spaces for indentation in PHP.
      - Use single quotes for strings in PHP and JavaScript.
      - Use camelCase for variable and function names in JavaScript.
      - Use PascalCase for class names in PHP.

  - name: Commenting
    description: >
      Ensure comments are utilized and used across the code for better visibility:
      - Use comments to explain complex logic and code blocks.
      - Include a comment header for each file with a brief description of its purpose.
      - Use TODO comments to indicate areas for future improvement.

  - name: Documentation
    description: >
      Maintain documentation for the project:
      - Document all functions and classes with PHPDoc or JSDoc.
      - Keep a changelog for major updates and features.
      - Maintain a README file with setup instructions and project overview.


